# Sampler
- Bypass the Sampler group when trying to finalize masks.
- Un-mute HiRes Fix group for final render to increase image quality.

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# Controlnet:
- Adjust weight values on Lineart, Depth, and Openpose to affect the output, will require experimentation.
- If you already have rendered Lineart, Depth, and Openpose videos, you can mute the Orange Generate groups and un-mute the Red Override groups and upload the respective videos to save on processing time.

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# Models:
- I recommend using an LCM model (I used ParadigmLCM v1.0) and adding the lora AnimateLCM\_sd15\_t2v\_lora.safetensors with strength 0.18.
- Set Loras in the Lora Stacker with associated weights.
- You can merge multiple models together using the Model Merge Stack to get various interesting effects. Make sure the weights add up to 1.0 for the enabled models.

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# AnimateDiff:
- You can change or bypass the motion lora, I use LiquidAF with weight 0.8 by default.
- Increase/decrease the Scale and Effect floats to increase/decrease the amount of motion in the output.

# Prompt:
- Input a batch positive prompt in the green text area and a negative prompt in the red text area.
- Batch Format example:

"0" :"4k, bright sunshine outdoor buddhist temple, stephen_strange (dark blue outfit, dark blue pants, dark brown boots), red shoulder pads",

"20": "4k, colorful flower field with swirls and multi-color petals, stephen_strange (dark blue outfit, dark blue pants, dark brown boots), red shoulder pads",

etc...

# IPAdapters:
### Red, Green, Blue:
- Subject mask reference images.
### Black:
- Background mask image, upload a reference image for the background.
### White:
- Dilation mask reference image, upload a reference image for the dilation mask in use.
### Yellow, Magenta:
- Voronoi Noise mask reference images.

### Tip:
- Only un-bypass the IPAdapters you need to save on VRAM.

# Output
- Change the output location of the video file by updating the custom_directory string.
- Videos are saved in ComfyUI/output/[date]/[custom_directory]

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# Input:
1. Input a subject video and select the max number of frames to load with frame\_load\_cap (if needed).
2. Select the output width and height of the video
3. You can set every\_nth to 2 or more to use every other frame to reduce rendering time if needed.
4. Start later in the video using skip\_frames.
4. Choose a seed value

# Composite Output
- Used to composite original footage onto sampler output based on latent noise mask.
- You can mute each composite group to prevent input video from being composited onto the final result.

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# Audio Processing:
- This section takes in audio from the input video, extracts the stems (bass, drums, vocals, etc.) and then converts it to a normalized amplitude synced with the input video frames.
- amp_control = total range the amplitude can travel.
- amp_offset = the minimum value the amplitude can take.
- Example: amp\_control = 0.8 and amp\_offset = 0.2 means the signal will travel between 0.2 and 1.0.

### Tips:
- Sometimes the Drums stem will have the actual Bass notes of the song, preview each to see which to use for your masks.
- Use the graphs to get a good understanding of how the signal for that stem changes over the length of the video

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# Voronoi Generators:
- This section is used to generate the audioreactive noise shapes that will compose part of the background behind your subject.
- The most significant changes to the look of the noise will come from changing the "distance_metric" functions on each of the Voronoi generator nodes.
- You can also change the"formula" on the Scale Scheduler node to change movement patterns of the noise.

### Tips:
- Increase the values on the randomness scheduler to break up symmetrical patterns.
- Experiment with different values for the Detail Scheduler to affect the output.

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# Audio Masks:
- This section takes the raw output from the voronoi generators, adds movement to the shapes to match the selected audio stem, converts the noise into a mask, and colors the mask to be used in compositing.
- Play around with settings for Lag Chop, Rescale Float List, and Keyframe Scheduler to change how fast and slow the noise moves, and how much of the noise to convert into a mask.

### Tips:
- Lower Lag Chop values increase the amount of "Lag" on the movement.
- min on the Rescale Float List node refers to how "slow" the noise video will be with low amplitude, and max is how "fast" it moves on high amplitude signals.
- Keyframe scheduler sets the cutoff for comparing brightness values to create the mask. Lower values will result in more noise used in the final mask, while higher values will use less of the noise.

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# Audioreactive Dilate Masks:
- Adjust the min and max radius of the dilation mask which will grow and shrink depending on the current normalized amplitude value for that frame.
- You can change which subject the mask targets using the top-most node, by default it is set to subject\_mask\_red.
- You can also change which audio stem to base the audioreactivity on by changing the Get\_audio\_sync node from bass to drums and so on.
### Tips:
- Change the shape to "square" for faster processing speed when testing, it's less accurate but useful when setting things up.
- Un-mute Override Composite and mute the mask color group if you have a composite video already rendered to save on processing time.
- Bypass the audioreactive mask group if you don't want the "aura" around your subject
